The intruder had access to the production databases, potentially giving them access to unencrypted message data, password hashes and access tokens. Change your password now - no plaintext Matrix passwords were leaked, but weak passwords could still be cracked from the hashed passwords. Change your NickServ password - there's no evidence bridge credentials were compromised, but if you have given the IRC bridges credentials to your NickServ account we would recommend changing this password. The attacker did have access to the production database, so unencrypted content may be compromised. We weighed the risk of some users losing access to encrypted messages against that of all users' accounts being vulnerable to hijack via the compromised access tokens. April 4th Updated 2019-04-12 11:00 UTC.Attacker gains access to production infrastructure by hijacking a forwarded SSH agent logging into the compromised Jenkins worker. The defacement confirms that encrypted password hashes were exfiltrated from the production database, so it is even more important for everyone to change their password.